    <section id="import-auto-idm1408997072">
      <title>Introduction</title>
      <para id="import-auto-idm1350463312">As discussed in <link url="https://cnx.org/contents/uieDnVBC@23.1:DocvnWPK@1/XPS-Analysis-of-Modified-Surfa" window="new">XPS Analysis of Modified Surfaces</link>; X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy is a very useful surface analysis technique especially for metals. X-rays are absorbed by the atoms, and a single K shell electron is emitted. The binding energy of the electron is dependent on the environment and oxidation state of the atom.</para><para id="import-auto-idm1155913888">Compared to a ground state metal atom, a K shell electron from an oxidized metal will experience a greater coulombic interaction with the core. This will cause it to have a higher binding energy, as more energy is needed to emit the electron. The change in binding energy, the chemical shift, can be used to determine the oxidation state of the metal.</para>
      <para id="import-auto-idm1191090272">Different core levels in XPS can be analyzed. The nomenclature of core levels in XPS is nl<sub>j</sub>; n is the principal quantum number, l is the orbital angular quantum number (s orbital l = 0, p orbital l = 1, d orbital l = 2), and j is the total angular momentum quantum number given by l+s (where s is spin quantum number, ±½). So a Fe 2p<sub>3/2</sub> peak, for example, is looking at the 2p core of iron where the total angular momentum is 3/2.  </para><para id="import-auto-idm296143408">All orbitals, besides s, will give rise to a doublet due to spin-orbit splitting. When a p, d, or f level electron is removed by the XPS process, there will be coupling between the unpaired spin and orbital angular momentum. This results in two peaks whose ratios will vary depending on the orbital level. Spin-orbital splitting does not occur for s because the s orbital has zero orbital angular momentum.</para>
