</table><para id="import-auto-idm1341840720">Another thing to keep in mind is complex splitting. Some compounds will have multiplet splitting, where a core level for a single compound will appear as multiple peaks. An example is Cr<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3 </sub>2p<sub>3/2</sub>, which appears as multiple peaks (<link target-id="multiplet"/>). Multiple peaks could also appear due to “charge transfer satellites”, from the sudden creation of a core hole due to the XPS process.</para><figure id="multiplet"><media id="complexpeak" alt="">
            <image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/Picture 4-d466.png" width="300" print-width="3in"/>
          </media>
        <caption>High resolution Cr 2p<sub>3/2</sub> XPS peak for Cr<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub> showing an example of complex splitting. Adapted from K. Wright and A. R. Barron, <emphasis effect="italics">C</emphasis>, 2017, <emphasis effect="bold">3</emphasis>, 17. </caption></figure></section><section id="eip-917"><title>Summary</title><para id="eip-751">Despite its limitations, XPS is a powerful tool for determining metal oxidation states. By proper sample handling and understanding what species could be present in your sample, incorrect analysis due to oxygen contamination and complex splitting can be avoided. There are a wide variety of uses for this technique, such determining oxide composition in thin oxide films and determining carbon nanotube metal sandwich complexes.
